      <p>In addition to being more accurate than the other methods, PathoScope also outperformed RINS and ReadScan in terms of the computation time needed to complete the analysis. On a cluster node with 16 CPUs and 256Â GB of RAM, PathoScope 2.0 required an average of 17Â min of compute time, whereas ReadScan required an average of 50Â min and RINS required an average of more than 8Â h for the 30 completed samples (10 of the samples did not finish in less than 24Â h). PathoID version 1.0 was on average 3Â min faster than PathoID version 2.0, but this computational time increase is almost entirely due to added features in version 2.0, such as better genome annotation, detailed result reporting, and interaction with other PathoScope modules. We also repeated the experiment with a larger target database containing all bacterial sequences. Only PathoScope 2.0 was able to finish this run successfully in a reasonable computational timeframe (&lt;24Â h per sample).</p>
